Polymorphism(poly+morphism):  
A person has many form of itself but at a time only a single form will be executed.

In C language we have to remember these 4 functions name even they are performing the same task, this is bec in C lang we dont have polymorphism.
absint(int) -> absolute value of int
absfloat(float) -> absolute value of float
absdouble(double) -> absolute value of double
abschar(char) -> absolute value of char

But in C++ and java bec we have polymorphism so we can have multiple functions of same name.
abs(int)
abs(float)
abs(double)
abs(char)
same function but have many forms an example of polymorphism.

On the basis of time there are mainly 2 types of polymorphism- Compile time and runtime

1. Compile time Polymorphism(static,early binding): If we are able to find at compile time that which form of the specific method will be executed is k/a compile-time polymorphism.
Because it is defined at compile time that whcih form will be executed so it is called early binding.
which method will be execute is decided by reference variable.

class A {
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("1");
    }
    public void m1(int x){
        System.out.println(x);
    }
    public void m1(double y){
        System.out.println(y);
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        A a = new A();
        a.m1();// decide at compile time
        a.m1(10);// decide at compile time
        a.m1(10.4);// decide at compile time
    }
}

examples of CTP-
method overloading:
defining multiple forms of same name method inside a class called method overloading.

class A {
    public void m1(int i){
        System.out.println(i);
    }
     public void m1(float d){
        System.out.println(d+10);
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        A a = new A();
        a.m1(10);//calls 1st form of m1
        a.m1('a');//calls 1st form of m1, bec we can store a char into int and it prints the unicode value of a
        a.m1(10l);//calls 2nd form of m1, bec we can store long into double
        a.m1(10.5);//error:The method m1(int) in the type A is not applicable for the arguments (double)
    }
}

2. Runtime polymorphism(late binding/Dynamic): Which method will be called is decided at runtime. Parent and child have same name methods.

example of RTP -
method Overriding: If child is not satisfied with the method of parent then child can change the method this is known as method overriding.
class parent{
    public void m1(){//Overridden method: method which is overrided
        System.out.println("1");
    }
}
class child extends parent{
    public void m1(){//Override method:method which overrides the another method 
        System.out.println("4");
    }
}
whcih method will be called is decided by the objects in overriding but in overloading decided by ref. variable.

