Overriding is only when parent class method and child class method both are non static.

Case1: parent has non-static method and child has static.
class parent{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("1");
    }
}
class child extends parent {
    public static void m1(){//Error in m1(): This static method cannot hide the instance method from parent
        System.out.println("2");
    }
}
This is not overriding bec. parent have non static method and child have static.
Child's m1() method will load first in the memory due to static, then parent method will load when we creat parent class object.
Both methods have different loading time but it has to be the same.

Case2: parent has static method and child has non-static.
class parent{
    public static void m1(){
        System.out.println("1");
    }
}
class child extends parent {
    public void m1(){//Error in m1(): This instance method cannot override the static method from parent
        System.out.println("2");
    }
}
Here also no overriding bec. parent have static method and child hav non static method.

Case3: Both parent and child have static method.
class parent{
    public static void m1(){
        System.out.println("1");
    }
}
class child extends parent {
    public static void m1(){
        System.out.println("2");
    }
}
Here the m1() method child get from parent is hided due to own created m1() method by child. (Method hiding)

